<h2>How to Run a GEO Audit on Your Content</h2>
<p>You do not need paid tools to assess your GEO readiness. Here is a manual audit process based on the GEO-16 framework.</p>
<h3>Step 1: Check Technical Foundations</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Verify <code>robots.txt</code> allows GPTBot, PerplexityBot, and ClaudeBot. Read our <a href="/blog/ai-crawlers-guide/">AI crawlers guide</a>.</li>
<li>[ ] Confirm pages use server-side rendering or static HTML (not client-side JS only)</li>
<li>[ ] Check that an <a href="/blog/llms-txt-guide/">llms.txt file</a> exists and maps your site structure</li>
<li>[ ] Verify HTTPS is active across all pages</li>
<li>[ ] Test page speed (under 3 seconds load time)</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 2: Audit Content Structure</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Every page has a clear H1, H2, H3 hierarchy with no skipped levels</li>
<li>[ ] Key definitions appear in the first 2 sentences of each section</li>
<li>[ ] Content uses numbered lists, bullet points, and tables for structured data</li>
<li>[ ] FAQ sections exist on informational and commercial pages</li>
<li>[ ] Follow the <a href="/blog/blog-geo-checklist/">blog GEO checklist</a> for every article</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 3: Verify Schema Markup</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Article/BlogPosting schema on all blog posts</li>
<li>[ ] FAQPage schema on pages with FAQ sections</li>
<li>[ ] Organization schema on your about page</li>
<li>[ ] Product/Offer schema on pricing and product pages</li>
<li>[ ] Author schema with credentials on content pages</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 4: Assess Authority Signals</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Author bylines with credentials on every article</li>
<li>[ ] External citations to authoritative sources (2+ per article)</li>
<li>[ ] <a href="/blog/eeat-google-quality-guide/">E-E-A-T signals</a> present (experience, expertise, authority, trust)</li>
<li>[ ] Brand profiles active on G2, Trustpilot, or industry review platforms</li>
<li>[ ] Consistent entity information (name, description) across web properties</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 5: Evaluate Freshness</h3>
<ul>
<li>[ ] Top 20 pages updated within the last 90 days</li>
<li>[ ] Publication dates and "last updated" timestamps visible</li>
<li>[ ] No outdated statistics or year references</li>
<li>[ ] Regular publishing cadence (weekly or more frequent)</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 6: Score Each Page</h3>
<p>Rate each of the 16 pillars from 0 (not present) to 1 (fully optimized). Sum the scores. Divide by 16. This gives you a normalized GEO score from 0 to 1.</p>
<p><strong>Interpretation:</strong>
- 0.70 to 1.00: Strong GEO readiness. Focus on monitoring and maintaining.
- 0.50 to 0.69: Moderate. Prioritize the 3 weakest pillars for improvement.
- Below 0.50: Low. Start with technical foundations and content structure.</p>
<h2>How to Improve Your GEO Score</h2>
<p>Improving your GEO score follows the same priority logic as the GEO-16 framework. Fix the highest-impact pillars first.</p>
<h3>Priority 1: Metadata and Freshness (Week 1)</h3>
<p>This single pillar has the highest correlation with AI citations (+47%). Quick wins:</p>
<ul>
<li>Add or update <code>&lt;meta&gt;</code> descriptions with clear, factual summaries</li>
<li>Include publication date and "last updated" date on every page</li>
<li>Update your top 10 traffic pages with fresh statistics and current-year references</li>
<li>Remove any content with outdated data that contradicts current facts</li>
<li>Set a quarterly refresh schedule for high-value pages</li>
</ul>
<p>Our guide on <a href="/blog/update-old-blog-posts/">updating old blog posts</a> covers the full refresh process.</p>
<h3>Priority 2: Semantic HTML and Structured Data (Week 2)</h3>
<p>These 2 pillars combine for the second-largest citation impact:</p>
<ul>
<li>Restructure headings to follow proper H1 &gt; H2 &gt; H3 hierarchy</li>
<li>Add JSON-LD Article schema to every blog post</li>
<li>Add FAQPage schema to every page with FAQ content</li>
<li>Use <code>&lt;table&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;ul&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;ol&gt;</code> elements instead of formatting hacks</li>
